<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25041f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25041f">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25041f"> 41(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ultimogeniture</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In several customs which divide the inheritance equally among sons, the youngest keeps the homestead, the aster or hearth. I am far from saying that the servile origin of <mark>ultimogeniture</mark> is proved, but certainly the succession of the youngest was regarded as servile in the thirteenth century. <small> Sir James Frazer, <a name="FLOT2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FLOT2"><cite title="source">Folk-Lore in the Old Testament</cite></a> (1923) 176</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Ultimogeniture</i> or <i>postremogeniture</i> (junior right) is the tradition of inheritance by the <u>last-born</u> of a privileged position in a parent&apos;s wealth or office. The tradition is far rarer historically than is <i>primogeniture</i>, the sole inheritance by the first-born, or <i>partible inheritance</i>, the division of the estate equally among the children).  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14021e" href="c14all.htm#c14021e">VI.C.14:021(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
